<DOC><DOCNO> AP890923-0034 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0533EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Hugo-CaribbeanToll     09-23 0233</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hugo-Caribbean Toll,0246</SECOND><HEAD>Deaths Caused by Hurricane Hugo in Caribbean</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   According to latest figures available, 27 to 29 people died whenHurricane Hugo plowed across the islands of the northeast Caribbeanearlier this week, razing homes, cutting power and communicationsand leaving thousands without fresh water.   Six others died Wednesday when a French rescue helicopter crashedoff Guadeloupe.   Here's an island-by-island look at the deaths in the Caribbean.</TEXT><TEXT>   PUERTO RICO _ Six people were killed, including four by drowningand electrocution, according to police.</TEXT><TEXT>   U.S. VIRGIN ISLANDS _ Lt. Gov. Derek Hodge said four people werekilled on St. Croix. However, Evelyn Crittenden, vice chairman ofthe island's Red Cross, put the number at six. There has been noinformation yet of any deaths on St. Thomas and St. John. </TEXT><TEXT>   MONTSERRAT _ Ten died on this British island, according toGovernor-General Christopher Turner.</TEXT><TEXT>   GUADELOUPE _ Five were killed during the hurricane in this Frenchoverseas department, according to French government officials on thesister island of Martinique. Six more died in the crash of a Frenchrescue helicopter, according to the French Defense Ministry in Paris.</TEXT><TEXT>   ANTIGUA _ Two were killed in this former British colony,according to officials.</TEXT><TEXT>   ST. KITTS and NEVIS _ It is unknown whether there were deaths orinjuries because communications to this island federation remainknocked out.</TEXT></DOC>